INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cf78a3ba-1cba-4cff-a02f-8c8842bc7907',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Tableau's Chart Selection Philosophy — Matching Marks to Data Structure and Audience$escape$,
  $escape$Tableau's Show Me panel surfaces 24 chart types, but selection should follow data structure, not aesthetic instinct. The core rule: match the mark type to the field combination on your shelves.

Two Dimensions + one Measure → bar or heatmap (drag Measure to Color with SUM aggregation). One date field + one Measure → line chart — only when the date is a continuous green pill; a discrete date pill produces disconnected segment bars, not a trend line. Two Measures on Rows and Columns shelves → scatter plot; add a third Measure to Size for a bubble chart.

Audience context reshapes the decision: executive dashboards favor big-number KPI tiles — use WINDOW_MAX() table calculations for period-over-period delta — and horizontal bars sorted DESC. Analyst workbooks benefit from scatter plots augmented with reference lines via the Analytics pane. For dual-axis charts, right-click the secondary axis and select Synchronize Axis only when both measures share the same scale; mismatched axes mislead silently. Avoid pie charts beyond five marks — Tableau's angle encoding degrades fast, and a sorted bar communicates the same ranking unambiguously.$escape$,
  NULL,
  NULL,
