INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '32143039-5063-452d-be9e-4a570a7c4649',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Tableau LOD Expressions — FIXED vs INCLUDE vs EXCLUDE and When to Use Each$escape$,
  $escape$LOD expressions let you control the granularity of a calculation independent of the view's level of detail. FIXED computes at a specified dimension regardless of filters — except context filters, which execute before FIXED. INCLUDE adds dimensions to the view's grain, useful when you need a finer calculation than what's on the viz (e.g., average of per-user revenue within a region). EXCLUDE removes a dimension from the current grain — ideal for percent-of-total without table calculations.

Performance tip: FIXED LOD expressions generate a subquery in the SQL sent to your data source. Stacking multiple FIXED LODs on a single viz creates multiple subqueries joined back to the primary. On large extracts or live connections, this compounds fast. Prefer INCLUDE/EXCLUDE when you can — they fold into the main query. For FIXED, use context filters strategically to narrow the subquery early.

Dashboard design: replace table calculations like WINDOW_AVG with FIXED LODs when results need to be stable across different filter selections. Table calcs recompute per partition; LODs are filter-aware only at the dimension level you declare.$escape$,
  $escape$// Calculated field examples in Tableau

// FIXED — customer's first order date, ignores view filters
{ FIXED [Customer ID] : MIN([Order Date]) }

// INCLUDE — average order value per customer, within the region in view
{ INCLUDE [Customer ID] : AVG([Sales]) }

// EXCLUDE — region's share of total (removes Sub-Category from grain)
[Sales] / { EXCLUDE [Sub-Category] : SUM([Sales]) }

// Context filter pattern: drag [Region] to Context
// before using FIXED to scope the subquery to filtered rows only$escape$,
