INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd7ba1b3c-df3c-466b-a61e-80cc5fff3e07',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Tableau + Cube Metrics Layer — One Definition, Zero Drift Across Workbooks$escape$,
  $escape$Scattered calculated fields across Tableau workbooks are a metrics consistency nightmare — three dashboards, three definitions of 'revenue'. A semantic metrics layer centralizes that logic outside Tableau entirely.

Cube.dev exposes a Postgres-compatible SQL API that Tableau connects to via the built-in PostgreSQL connector (host: your Cube Cloud endpoint, port 5432). Once live, Cube cubes appear as tables in Tableau's Data Source pane — measures like `revenue` and `avg_order_value` surface as pre-aggregated fields. No LOD expressions needed for standard business KPIs.

dbt's Semantic Layer (MetricFlow) works similarly: point Tableau at the dbt Semantic Layer JDBC driver (supported from Tableau Desktop 2023.2+), authenticate via your dbt Cloud environment ID, and MetricFlow-defined metrics become queryable columns. Both paths mean analysts drag consistent, governance-approved measures instead of reimplementing `SUM(IF([status]='completed',[amount],0))` per workbook.

The Cube schema below defines `revenue` and `avg_order_value` once. Every Tableau workbook connecting to that endpoint queries identical logic — no Published Data Source sprawl, no metric drift.$escape$,
  $escape$// cube.js schema — metrics defined once, consumed by Tableau via Postgres SQL API
cube(`Orders`, {
  sql: `SELECT * FROM orders`,
  measures: {
    revenue: {
      sql: `amount`,
      type: `sum`,
      filters: [{ sql: `${CUBE}.status = 'completed'` }],
    },
    avg_order_value: {
      sql: `${revenue} / NULLIF(${count}, 0)`,
      type: `number`,
      format: `currency`,
    },
  },
  dimensions: {
    created_at: { sql: `created_at`, type: `time` },
    region:     { sql: `region`,     type: `string` },
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
